<br>
Playing on EQ is such a unique social setting that even when the rules of basic social contact seem obvious to us, they might not be to other people.  And before anyone suggests that the rules of social interaction in Norrath are the same as in Real Life, when was the last time you hailed a random guy on the street and asked &quot;R U a Lawyer?&quot; because you need one to join you &quot;group?&quot;  The rules are different, at least some of them, and I submit that Valancer clearly doesn't understand what the rules are here.<br>
<br>
Now, he's a pissy little jerk who very clearly deserves to be exposed to the consequences of his actions, as he has been (and how) and maybe he'll have learned something.  But the final obligation of society, to teach, has got to kick in sometime.  The final goal is not to tar and feather him and simply drive him off the server.  The goal is to help him learn better, and maybe make him a better person.<br>
<br>
I don't know how old the player of Valancer really is.  I'm not going to simply assume he's twelve, because that could easily be untrue.  But there *are* some twelve-year olds who play EQ, and when someone that age does something wrong you try to help them, you don't just leave them out in the cold.<br>
<br>
Valancer, if you are still reading this thread, get over the tired Little Brother (tm) routine and just come clean.  Admit you fucked up, incredibly so, and make a huge effort to earn the forgiveness of the *Person you wronged in the first place!*  This is just the peanut gallery on this board.  We are just the spectators.  You don't have anything to prove to us, really, except that you are willing to be responsible to the person you screwed over.  Earn his forgiveness and you've earned a second chance from at least 80% of the population here.  That's how society works.  Here, as well as most places.<br>
<br>
Send me a tell, sometime Valancer, if you want my advise in sorting this out.  It's an honest offer.  I can't promise I'll like you or be your friend, but I know what it's like to be in social situations that are just impossible to understand, and I'll try to help.  I had that kind of problem once myself, though not EQ related in the least.<br>
<br>
Remember folks.  People who have completely fucked-up need to be held responsible for their actions, I entirely agree, but they also need some opportunity to do better, or there's no point at all in expecting them to learn.<br>
<br>
Valquiss Silverpalm<br>
